### Healthcare

The provision of healthcare in Subang Jaya is primarily facilitated by two prominent private medical institutions. These are the Sime Darby Medical Centre Subang Jaya, which was formerly and perhaps more simply known as Subang Jaya Medical Centre (SJMC) in SS12, and the equally significant [Sunway Medical Centre](/Sunway_Medical_Centre) located within the expansive confines of [Bandar Sunway](/Bandar_Sunway). These facilities cater to those who can afford the premium for private care, or perhaps, for those who simply prefer it.

Under the auspices of the [9th Malaysian Plan](/9th_Malaysian_Plan), Subang Jaya also saw the establishment of its inaugural public health clinic, aptly named 1 Malaysia Healthcare. Situated in the Taman Subang Mewah area of USJ 1, its stated primary objective is to offer more affordable healthcare services to the lower and middle-income segments of the population, a noble, if often challenging, endeavor.

### Development

The landscape of Subang Jaya is in a perpetual state of flux, constantly being reshaped by ambitious development projects, a testament to the relentless human desire for "progress." Currently, the [Subang Jaya City Council](/Subang_Jaya_City_Council) oversees three substantial mixed commercial developments: SJCC Subang, SJ7 Trans-City, and Tropicana Metropark. SJCC Subang and SJ7 Trans-City, both spearheaded by [Sime Darby](/Sime_Darby), are envisioned as large-scale, integrated mixed developments, designed to seamlessly connect with highly advanced public transportation networks—a necessity, one might argue, given the sheer number of people they are expected to attract.

Further contributing to this urban tapestry are Da Men and Empire Remix, both strategically located in USJ 1. Da Men is a mixed commercial development sprawling across 8.6 acres (3.5 ha) of what is optimistically termed "prime land." It comprises two blocks of serviced apartments, a multitude of retail lots, and a six-story shopping podium—a self-contained ecosystem of living and consumption. Empire Remix, on the other hand, also presents itself as a mixed commercial development, featuring several blocks of office buildings, more serviced apartments, and yet another shopping mall, catering to the ever-present demand for both work and retail therapy.

Tropicana Metropark, an expansive 88.5-acre (35.8 ha) development, is designed to house over ten high-rise buildings. This includes a varied mix of office suites, SOHO (Small Office, Home Office) units, towering office blocks, business suites, villas (for those who prefer horizontal living amidst the vertical), shopfronts, and, of course, a shopping mall. It is strategically positioned near the more upscale neighborhoods of USJ Heights and Subang Heights, offering convenient access directly from the [Federal Highway](/Federal_Highway,_Malaysia). To alleviate the inevitable traffic congestion, a new direct access from the [Federal Highway](/Federal_Highway,_Malaysia) was slated for completion by 2016, a small concession to the urban reality. Moreover, Bandar Raya Developments Bhd (BRDB) is contributing to this relentless expansion with its own RM2 billion integrated mixed development project, covering 24 acres in the same vicinity. One can only hope the infrastructure keeps pace with the ambition.

### Transportation

Subang Jaya, in its characteristic fashion, is not merely a collection of buildings but a highly interconnected nexus, seamlessly linked to the vibrant cities of [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur) and [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam), as well as to the various townships of [Petaling Jaya](/Petaling_Jaya), including [Ara Damansara](/Ara_Damansara), [Kota Damansara](/Kota_Damansara), [Bandar Utama](/Bandar_Utama), [Damansara Utama](/Damansara_Utama), and [Mutiara Damansara](/Mutiara_Damansara). This impressive connectivity is achieved through a dense network of major highways, a testament to the Malaysian penchant for asphalt: the venerable [Federal Highway](/Federal_Highway), the [Shah Alam Expressway](/Shah_Alam_Expressway) (KESAS), the [New Klang Valley Expressway](/New_Klang_Valley_Expressway) (NKVE), the [New Pantai Expressway](/New_Pantai_Expressway) (NPE), the [North–South Expressway Central Link](/North%E2%80%93South_Expressway_Central_Link), and the [Damansara–Puchong Expressway](/Damansara%E2%80%93Puchong_Expressway) (LDP). Access from the [Federal Highway](/Federal_Highway) into Subang Jaya is provided by three distinct exits: the two primary routes via exit 17.9 km through [Persiaran Kewajipan](/Persiaran_Kewajipan) and exit 18.2 km through [Persiaran Tujuan](/Persiaran_Tujuan), with an alternative exit offered via Persiaran Teknologi Subang at Tropicana Metropark's dedicated interchange.

[Persiaran Kewajipan](/Persiaran_Kewajipan) and [Persiaran Tujuan](/Persiaran_Tujuan) bear the burden of serving as the two principal arterial roads within Subang Jaya, channeling the ceaseless flow of traffic. An alternative route for commuters traveling from [USJ](/UEP_Subang_Jaya) and Subang Jaya towards [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur) and [Petaling Jaya](/Petaling_Jaya) is the [Subang–Kelana Jaya Link](/Subang%E2%80%93Kelana_Jaya_Link). This link ingeniously connects the [Persiaran Kewajipan](/Persiaran_Kewajipan) roundabout of the [New Pantai Expressway](/New_Pantai_Expressway) to the [Subang Airport](/Subang_Airport) expressway (route 15), which in turn links to the [Federal Highway](/Federal_Highway,_Malaysia) ([Federal Route 2](/Malaysia_Federal_Route_2)). It's a marvel of interconnectedness, if one appreciates such things.

The public transport system in Subang Jaya is, by any measure, remarkably developed, a complex web designed to move masses of people with varying degrees of efficiency. It proudly boasts two distinct [Light Rail Transit](/Light_Rail_Transit) (LRT) lines, one [KTM Komuter](/KTM_Komuter) line, one [Bus Rapid Transit](/Bus_Rapid_Transit) (BRT) line, and the ubiquitous presence of bus and taxi services. Since 30 June 2016, a significant expansion of the [Kelana Jaya Line](/Kelana_Jaya_Line) has opened, extending its reach to connect various areas within Subang Jaya directly with the [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur) city center and [Petaling Jaya](/Petaling_Jaya). The LRT stations, as if by design, are strategically positioned within convenient walking distance of shopping malls, commercial centers, and residential areas, further supported by a network of feeder buses to bridge the last mile. The [Kelana Jaya Line](/Kelana_Jaya_Line) underwent an extension from its existing route at the Subang LRT Depot, traversing through the Dana 1 commercial center in [Kelana Jaya](/Kelana_Jaya), then onward to Kelana Centre Point, and finally reaching [Subang Parade](/Subang_Parade) (where it offers an interchange with the [KTM](/KTM) Subang Jaya commuter station), effectively covering three stations within the town center itself. Within [USJ](/UEP_Subang_Jaya), the LRT line continues its journey from SS18 to USJ 7 (serving Da Men and Summit), USJ Taipan, Wawasan (USJ 15), USJ 21 (connecting to One City and Main Place), and culminates at the main interchange station hub in [Putra Heights](/Putra_Heights). This hub, a nexus of urban mobility, provides a crucial connection to another LRT line, the [Sri Petaling Line](/Sri_Petaling_Line), which extends its reach to [Puchong](/Puchong), [Bukit Jalil](/Bukit_Jalil), and [Sri Petaling](/Sri_Petaling). Furthermore, for those residing in the southern reaches of the [Subang Jaya City Council](/Subang_Jaya_City_Council) area, six stations of the [MRT Putrajaya line](/Putrajaya_line) are strategically located, serving the communities of [Seri Kembangan](/Seri_Kembangan) and Serdang. It's a truly intricate dance of routes and connections.

Public bus transportation, a more grounded mode of transit, is diligently provided by two primary companies: [RapidKL](/RapidKL) and [Metrobus](/Metrobus_Nationwide). These services ensure accessibility within the town itself and offer vital connections to [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur). As an alternative, the [Bus Rapid Transit](/Bus_Rapid_Transit) (BRT) line connects the [Setia Jaya Komuter station](/Setia_Jaya_Komuter_station) through [Bandar Sunway](/Bandar_Sunway) to the [USJ7 LRT Station](/USJ7_LRT_Station). The [BRT Sunway Line](/BRT_Sunway_Line) commenced its operations on 1 June 2015, following its official launch by then-prime minister of Malaysia, [Najib Razak](/Najib_Razak). This BRT service represents a public-private partnership, a collaboration between Prasarana and Sunway Group, with the commendable aim of providing eco-friendly electric bus services that glide along elevated tracks for the convenience of residents in [Bandar Sunway](/Bandar_Sunway) and [USJ](/UEP_Subang_Jaya).

For commuter train services, Subang Jaya is well-served by an urban-suburban rail link, the [KTM](/Keretapi_Tanah_Melayu) Komuter. This provides essential transportation links towards the port town of [Port Klang](/Port_Klang) and the capital city of [Kuala Lumpur](/Kuala_Lumpur), offering a respite from the often-congested roads.

Finally, for those who prefer to take to the skies, the [Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport](/Sultan_Abdul_Aziz_Shah_Airport) is conveniently located at [Subang](/Subang,_Selangor), within the larger administrative area of [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam). It functions as the primary hub for turboprop airlines such as [Firefly](/Firefly_(airline)) (a low-cost carrier subsidiary of Malaysia Airlines), Malindo Air, and [Berjaya Air](/Berjaya_Air). Beyond commercial flights, it also proudly serves as the premier hub for corporate and private aviation across Southeast Asia, catering to a clientele with less patience for the common man's travel woes.

